.github: initial release general

The idea is to:

 1. Update VERSION
 2. Update ChangeLog.md with release info (remember link at bottom)
 3. Tag the commit with the new release vX.Y (optionally .Z)

When pushing the tag a this job is started, which runs the 'release'
target from the top Makefile, which in turn generates the Doxygen API
documentation, runs 'distcheck' and then uploades the resulting files
to the new GitHub release.

.github: run unit-tests as sudo for macOS

The Linux tests run inside an unshare, but I could not find any better
way than "sudo", unfortunately, to get the tests to pass on macOS:

We get the following error on macOS:

    [ERROR]: libnet_bpf_open(): open(): (/dev/bpf0): Permission denied

There is a possibility that the macOS runner can be set up to allow
access to that device node using something like:

    chgrp access_bpf /dev/bpf*
    chmod g+rw /dev/bpf*

An even better alternative would be to investigate this shiny new thing:

    https://macoscontainers.org

Integrate CMocka with autotools and wrap tests in an unshare

This adds a proper TAP driver to run the CMocka unit tests by the
standard autotools command:

    make check

Each test is run in a dedicated network namespace so they can run
in true parallel.  A fake network is created in test/setup.sh

Note: the primary reason for this change is to be able to run the
      unit tests (on Linux) without having to be root (sudo).  A
      secondary reason is that test/Makefile.am should never set
      the bin_PROGRAMS variable since that is for binaries that
      should be installed.  Any non-Linux system out there can
      have their own TESTS_ENVIRONMENT, or run them as root.

commit.message:
udld: initial support

Summary of changes:
- Complete UDLD protocol support was added according to RFC5171
- UDLD checksum implementation was added
- UDLD unit tests were added
- CI has been updated to run UDLD unit tests

That's how sample/udld looks in tcpdump:
